# When to delete, when to defer

## Default: delete

Code with no live caller, code that handles state that doesn't exist, code
marked `[[deprecated]]` for more than one release cycle — all of it goes. Dead
code is audit surface, attack surface, and review fatigue.

## When to use `[[deprecated]]`

Almost never. The annotation is a promise to delete by a specific version. If
you can't name the version, you can't deprecate — delete now or schedule the
deletion in `docs/FOLLOWUPS.md`. `[[deprecated]]` without a deletion date is
debt that compounds.

## Migration code is a permanent attack surface for a one-time problem

Code that detects an old format and converts it runs forever to handle state
that exists for a finite period.

- **Pre-V3 launch:** `rm -rf ~/.shekyl` and re-sync is the migration path. No
  in-Shekyl format-detection code is justified. Ruthless about deletion.
- **Post-V3 launch:** real users have real state. Migration code becomes
  load-bearing where it exists, but should be the smallest possible code with
  the clearest possible scope, and should still have a deletion target.

This rule is distinct from `60-no-monero-legacy.mdc`, which says no Monero-era
compatibility code exists at all — that's a permanent fact about genesis, not
a transitional policy.

## FOLLOWUPS.md is not a graveyard

Items in `docs/FOLLOWUPS.md` have a target version (V3.1, V3.2, V4). Items
without a target version get one within 30 days or get closed as "won't fix."

## "While we're here" is the enemy

Every PR has a stated scope. Changes outside that scope go in a separate PR,
even when they're obvious improvements. Reviewer attention is finite;
bisection requires small commits. When you spot something worth fixing
outside scope, write it down in `FOLLOWUPS.md` and keep going.

## V3.x as the long-term platform

V3 ships with FCMP++ and hybrid PQC from genesis. V4 (lattice-only) is gated
on external standardization (NIST lattice threshold algorithms) and may be
12–24 months away. Between those points, V3.x is where improvements land:

- V3.1: transfer_details Rust migration, audit response
- V3.2: wallet_rpc_server Rust cutover, performance work
- V3.3+: as findings emerge

Items that don't fit V3.0 don't have to wait for V4.
